@NODE background "WatchWatcher - background"
                                Background
                                ----------
Have you ever encountered programs that overwrites your system clock?
It's mostly old games, demos and sometimes strange system hangups also
causes the date to be set to an incorrect value. This results in a clock
set to often insane values, sometimes it's 1989 (travelling back in time?)
and sometimes the clock says that the date is 2001 (amazing having an
computer that can travel into the future!!!)
All this makes me mad, so I wrote this little program to help me overcome
these problems.

Yes, I do know that there are millions of other programs that do the same
thing as WatchWatcher, but of course there is none in F.Ultra style ;-)
@ENDNODE
@NODE requirements "The requirements"
WatchWatcher should run without any problem on any Amiga in the world with
atleast Kickstart v36+ (that is OS v2.00+) and an MC680x0. I have even
tested it with UAE (Unix Amiga Emulator) and it worked fine. But if you
would encounter any problems with your system, @{"please let me know." link contact}

WatchWatcher was developed on an old A500 equipped with the following:

                        CPU:       MC68000 7MHZ
                        KICKSTART: v40.70 (OS 3.1)
                        GRAPHICS:  OCS/ECS
                        CHIP:      1.5 MB
                        FAST:      8 MB
                        HARDDRIVE: 126 MB

I know that it's A BIT lowend, but as soon as I get myself a job, I will
run out on the street and buy myself the biggest and fastest Amiga alive.
@ENDNODE
@NODE installation "How to install WatchWatcher"
Installation is very easy and basic. Simply decide whether you want to run
WatchWatcher from your Wbstartup-drawer, your startup-sequence or your
user-startup.
Novice users should install WatchWatcher in the WBstartup-drawer, while the
more advanced users might consider the startup-sequence.


                Installing WatchWatcher into the WBstartup
                ------------------------------------------
First single click on the WatchWatcher icon and drag it into the WbStartup
drawer. That's it, now WatchWatcher will automatically check your systime
every time you boot your computer. If you want to configure the way
WatchWatcher works, head over to the @{"configuration" link configuration} section and read about
the TOOLTYPES.


             Installing WatchWatcher for the startup-sequence
             ------------------------------------------------
Copy WatchWatcher (don't bother to copy the icon) to a location of your own
choice, preferable the C: drawer. Then edit your startup-sequence or your
user-sequence to execute WatchWatcher just before the LoadWB command. Note
that there is no need to RUN WatchWatcher, simply type "C:WatchWatcher". If
you want to configure the way WatchWatcher works, head over to the
@{"configuration" link configuration} section and read about the CLI_ARGUMENTS.
@ENDNODE
@NODE configuration "How to configure WatchWatcher"
                                 @{b}@{u}ToolTypes@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}PREFS_PATH@{ub} is the complete path to the timeprefs program that WatchWatcher
           would execute in order to change the time and date.
           The default is: sys:prefs/time

@{b}DAY_LIMIT@{ub}  is the maximum number of days ahead, that WatchWatcher will not
           ask you if the clock is sane. This should be set to the normal
           maximum of days that your computer is turned off.
           If set to 0, this check is turned off (useful for sysops and
           people who don't know how long their computers will be on or off).
           The default is set to two days. Read the @{"Technical section" link technical} for
           more details on how the DAY_LIMIT value works, it's described as
           the @{b}N@{ub} value in that section.


                               @{b}@{u}CLI Arguments@{ub}@{uu}

Template: WatchWatcher @{b}PATH@{ub},@{b}N@{ub}/N/K

@{b}PATH@{ub} is the complete path to the timeprefs program that WatchWatcher
     would execute in order to change the time and date.
     The default is: sys:prefs/time

@{b}N@{ub}    is the maximum number of days ahead, that WatchWatcher will not
     ask you if the clock is sane. This should be set to the normal
     maximum of days that your computer is turned off.
     If set to 0, this check is turned off (usefull for sysops and
     people who don't know how long their computers will be on or off).

     The default is set to two days. Read the @{"Technical section" link technical} for more
     details on how the N value really works.

Example: If your computer normally is turned off for five days at most and
you use a custom program to set the time and date that is called
"CyberDate" and that is place in the "work:download/cuber" directory, then
you should write like this: WatchWatcher work:download/cuber/CyberDate N=5
@ENDNODE
@NODE usage "How to use WatchWatcher"
@Next registration
There is not much to be said in this matter as WatchWatcher will do most of
it's work in silence. But when WatchWatcher detects a possible date
conflict, a requester will pop up that will look something like this:

                 +------------------------------------+-+
                 |Systemmessage                       |O|
                 |------------------------------------+-|
                 | There is a possible date conflict!   |
                 | Clock says date is: 1978-02-04       |
                 |                                      |
                 +--------------------------------------+
                 |@{"Change" link change}                        @{"Ignore" link ignore}|
                 +--------------------------------------+

Note that under Kick v38+ the date will be printed in localized format!
Under Kick v36 & v37 the date will be printed in dos format.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Ignore "Pressed the Ignore button?"
@NEXT usage
@PREV usage
If you press the IGNORE button, then WatchWatcher thinks OOPS I made a
mistake. Then it silently alters it's own filedate to the current and
quits.
@ENDNODE
@NODE change "Pressed the Change button?"
@NEXT usage
@PREV usage
If you press the CHANGE button, then WatchWatcher will execute the program
that you described in the PATH argument or PREFS_PATH tooltype. As default
this is set to "sys:prefs/time". Now you have the chance of correcting the
date. WatchWatcher will then silently alter it's own filedate to the new
and quit.
@ENDNODE
@NODE registration "How to register WatchWatcher"
@Prev usage
Registration is completely free and is done by @{"sending me an email" link contact} telling
me that you use WatchWatcher. I would also appreciate if you would tell me
with OS-version and CPU that you got. This will enable me to be sure of
which systems that WatchWatcher will work on. Please also write your
nationality, it's always nice to know where in the world I have my users.

But do note that there is NO special registrated version, I will simply add
you to my user-database so that I can send you mails about new versions of
WatchWatcher, and to study when I need encouragement ;-)
All information that you send me will ofcourse be strictly confidential.
@ENDNODE
