@NODE technical "The inner workings of WatchWatcher"
                              Technical Stuff
                              ---------------
First a word of warning, this text is VERY technical, sorry.

So how does WatchWatcher work?

Every file on your harddisk, floppydisk or ramdisk has something called:
last_modified_date. This is as the name tells the date when the file was
last modified (deleted or written to), if you type "list" in a shell window
you will see a list of files together with their last_modified_date.

Now to how WatchWatcher works:
At system bootup, WatchWatcher is executed from your Wbstartup, or your
s:startup-sequence (s:user-startup). When executed WatchWatcher reads it's
own last_modified_date. Then it fetches the systemtime.
When all this is done, WatchWatcher compares these two dates. If the
last_modified_date is newer than the systemtime then the clock is
considered insane (how will you otherwise explain that todays date is later
than when you first installed WatchWatcher???). When this is done,
WhatchWatchers checks the dates again, but this time it compares the
systemtime with last_modified_date+N (where N is a variable that can be set
to different values using @{"tooltypes or cli arguments" link configuration}, the default is 2).

Now if the systemtime is newer than last_modified_date+N then the clock is
once again considered insane.

If the clock is considered insane (that is, set to a wrong date) then
WatchWatcher will bring up an @{"intuition window" link usage} telling you that the clock
might be insane, and lets you choose if you want to IGNORE it (perhaps the
clock wasn't insane after all?) or CHANGE the time. If you press the IGNORE
button then the clock is considered sane again. And if you press the CHANGE
button then WatchWatcher will execute the sys:prefs/time (by default, but
this can be changed using @{"tooltypes or cli arguments" link configuration}!), so that you can
alter the time & date to the correct values. And now the clock is
considered sane again !!!!

If the clock now is considered sane, then WatchWatcher will alter it's
last_modified_date to that of the systemtime. This lets WatchWatcher to be
up to date so it can correctly check the systemtime at every bootup.

A nice and clean exit follows, releasing memory & library's used.
This whole procedure will take aprox less than 1 second, depending on disk
speed thou.

So what is the N value then????
Well in order to check the date in a correct way, the date must not only
be checked if it's to old, but also if it's to new (if it is set to far into
the future). It's here that N takes an important place!

Simply set N to the maximum days that you will have your computer turned
off (or turned on). Sysops and other people who's computers is turned off
or on for unknown periods should set N to 0 in order to disable this
feature. There is a much greater risk that the systemtime would be set to a
date in the past than into the future.
@ENDNODE
@NODE translate "Help me to translate WatchWatcher"
Adding locale support for a tiny application such as WatchWatcher would be
some kind of an overkill. Instead I have choosen to hardcode the language into
the executable. If you like to help me to translate WatchWatcher into other
languages then please @{"contact me" link contact} now. I will then send you all that you
need in order to perform the translation.
@ENDNODE
@NODE history "WatchWatcher's history"
                                  History
                                  -------
v1.3	Done some internal optimizations and added Swedish version.

v1.2	Minor update!
	Changed the order of the requester buttons so it will follow the
	Amiga UserInterface Guidelines. Now if you run any requester timeout
	patches, "Ignore" will be selected instead of "Change".


v1.1	Printed date as "-------" under kick v36. Now WatchWatcher outputs
	the date in format_dos style under v36 and format_def in v38+

	Passed wrong parameter (MODE_OLDFILE) to LVO_lock. Now WatchWatcher
	passes the right parameter (SHARED_LOCK). A very, very stupid bug!
	I don't know what I was thinking, sorry.

	Required v37+ although only v36+ functions are used. Now WatchWatcher
	requires v36+

	Removed the source from the archive, if you want it, @{"send me an email." link contact}


v1.0a	Updated the docfile. Sorry but the doc in the first release was
	very broken. Thanks to Frederik Rosenkjaer and Audrey McCalla, who
	informed me of this error. Where would I be without caring users??

	Minor change to the binary, so it will run some nano seconds faster
	on a 68040 or 68060 equipped machine due to rescheduling (a very
	neglected fact in the programming community).

	Added the N=0 option to turn the future check off.

	Now the source code is included. Read & enjoy, but please don't
	alter it or release it without asking me first !!!

	Shortened the binary by 12 bytes !!! (wow, amazing)


v1.0	First public release.
@ENDNODE
